[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The first n terms of the series sum to approximately $\ln n+\gamma$ , where $\ln$ is the natural logarithm and $\gamma \approx 0.577$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Because the logarithm has arbitrarily large values, the harmonic series does not have a finite limit: it is a divergent series.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Its divergence was proven in the 14th century by Nicole Oresme using a precursor to the Cauchy condensation test for the convergence of infinite series.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It can also be proven to diverge by comparing the sum to an integral, according to the integral test for convergence.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The name of the harmonic series derives from the concept of overtones or harmonics in music: the wavelengths of the overtones of a vibrating string are ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ , ${\tfrac {1}{3}}$ , ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ , etc., of the string's fundamental wavelength.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Every term of the harmonic series after the first is the harmonic mean of the neighboring terms, so the terms form a harmonic progression; the phrases *harmonic mean* and *harmonic progression* likewise derive from music.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Beyond music, harmonic sequences have also had a certain popularity with architects.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] This was so particularly in the Baroque period, when architects used them to establish the proportions of floor plans, of elevations, and to establish harmonic relationships between both interior and exterior architectural details of churches and palaces.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The divergence of the harmonic series was first proven in 1350 by Nicole Oresme.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Oresme's work, and the contemporaneous work of Richard Swineshead on a different series, marked the first appearance of infinite series other than the geometric series in mathematics.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] However, this achievement fell into obscurity.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Additional proofs were published in the 17th century by Pietro Mengoli and by Jacob Bernoulli.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Bernoulli credited his brother Johann Bernoulli for finding the proof, and it was later included in Johann Bernoulli's collected works.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The partial sums of the harmonic series were named harmonic numbers, and given their usual notation $H_{n}$ , in 1968 by Donald Knuth.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It is a divergent series: as more terms of the series are included in partial sums of the series, the values of these partial sums grow arbitrarily large, beyond any finite limit.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Because it is a divergent series, it should be interpreted as a formal sum, an abstract mathematical expression combining the unit fractions, rather than as something that can be evaluated to a numeric value.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] There are many different proofs of the divergence of the harmonic series, surveyed in a 2006 paper by S.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The same argument proves more strongly that, for every positive integer k , $\sum _{n=1}^{2^{k}}{\frac {1}{n}}\geq 1+{\frac {k}{2}}$ This is the original proof given by Nicole Oresme in around 1350.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The Cauchy condensation test is a generalization of this argument.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It is possible to prove that the harmonic series diverges by comparing its sum with an improper integral.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Specifically, consider the arrangement of rectangles shown in the figure to the right.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Each rectangle is 1 unit wide and ${\tfrac {1}{n}}$ units high, so if the harmonic series converged then the total area of the rectangles would be the sum of the harmonic series.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The curve $y={\tfrac {1}{x}}$ stays entirely below the upper boundary of the rectangles, so the area under the curve (in the range of x from one to infinity that is covered by rectangles) would be less than the area of the union of the rectangles.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] However, the area under the curve is given by a divergent improper integral, $\int _{1}^{\infty }{\frac {1}{x}}\,dx=\infty .$ Because this integral does not converge, the sum cannot converge either.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In the figure to the right, shifting each rectangle to the left by 1 unit, would produce a sequence of rectangles whose boundary lies below the curve rather than above it.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Therefore, the sum converges if and only if the integral over the same range of the same function converges.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] When this equivalence is used to check the convergence of a sum by replacing it with an easier integral, it is known as the integral test for convergence.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] These numbers grow very slowly, with logarithmic growth, as can be seen from the integral test.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] More precisely, by the Euler–Maclaurin formula, $H_{n}=\ln n+\gamma +{\frac {1}{2n}}-\varepsilon _{n}$ where $\gamma \approx 0.5772$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant and $0\leq \varepsilon _{n}\leq 1/(8n^{2})$ which approaches 0 as n goes to infinity.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] No harmonic numbers are integers except for $H_{1}=1$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] One way to prove that $H_{n}$ is not an integer is to consider the highest power of two $2^{k}$ in the range from 1 to n .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] If M is the least common multiple of the numbers from 1 to n , then $H_{k}$ can be rewritten as a sum of fractions with equal denominators $H_{n}=\sum _{i=1}^{n}{\tfrac {M/i}{M}}$ in which only one of the numerators, $M/2^{k}$ , is odd and the rest are even, and (when $n>1$ ) M is itself even.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Therefore, the result is a fraction with an odd numerator and an even denominator, which cannot be an integer.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] More generally, any sequence of consecutive integers has a unique member divisible by a greater power of two than all the other sequence members, from which it follows by the same argument that no two harmonic numbers differ by an integer.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Another proof that the harmonic numbers are not integers observes that the denominator of $H_{n}$ must be divisible by all prime numbers greater than $n/2$ and less than or equal to n , and uses Bertrand's postulate to prove that this set of primes is non-empty.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The same argument implies more strongly that, except for $H_{1}=1$ , $H_{2}=1.5$ , and $H_{6}=2.45$ , no harmonic number can have a terminating decimal representation.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It has been conjectured that every prime number divides the numerators of only a finite subset of the harmonic numbers, but this remains unproven.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] This equation can be used to extend the definition to harmonic numbers with rational indices.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Many well-known mathematical problems have solutions involving the harmonic series and its partial sums.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The jeep problem or desert-crossing problem is included in a 9th-century problem collection by Alcuin, *Propositiones ad Acuendos Juvenes* (formulated in terms of camels rather than jeeps), but with an incorrect solution.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The problem asks how far into the desert a jeep can travel and return, starting from a base with n loads of fuel, by carrying some of the fuel into the desert and leaving it in depots.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The optimal solution involves placing depots spaced at distances ${\tfrac {r}{2n}},{\tfrac {r}{2(n-1)}},{\tfrac {r}{2(n-2)}},\dots$ from the starting point and each other, where r is the range of distance that the jeep can travel with a single load of fuel.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] On each trip out and back from the base, the jeep places one more depot, refueling at the other depots along the way, and placing as much fuel as it can in the newly placed depot while still leaving enough for itself to return to the previous depots and the base.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The divergence of the harmonic series implies that crossings of any length are possible with enough fuel.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] For instance, for Alcuin's version of the problem, $r=30$ : a camel can carry 30 measures of grain and can travel one leuca while eating a single measure, where a leuca is a unit of distance roughly equal to 2.3 kilometres (1.4 mi).
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The problem has $n=3$ : there are 90 measures of grain, enough to supply three trips.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] However, Alcuin instead asks how much grain can be transported a distance of 30 leucas without a final return trip, either stranding some camels in the desert or failing to account for the amount of grain consumed by camels on their return trips.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In the block-stacking problem, one must place a pile of n identical rectangular blocks, one per layer, so that they hang as far as possible over the edge of a table without falling.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The top block can be placed with ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ of its length extending beyond the next lower block.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] If it is placed in this way, the next block down needs to be placed with at most ${\tfrac {1}{2}}\cdot {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ of its length extending beyond the next lower block, so that the center of mass of the top two blocks is supported and they do not topple.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The third block needs to be placed with at most ${\tfrac {1}{2}}\cdot {\tfrac {1}{3}}$ of its length extending beyond the next lower block, so that the center of mass of the top three blocks is supported and they do not topple, and so on.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In this way, it is possible to place the n blocks in such a way that they extend ${\tfrac {1}{2}}H_{n}$ lengths beyond the table, where $H_{n}$ is the n th harmonic number.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The divergence of the harmonic series implies that there is no limit on how far beyond the table the block stack can extend.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] For stacks with one block per layer, no better solution is possible, but significantly more overhang can be achieved using stacks with more than one block per layer.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The left equality comes from applying the distributive law to the product and recognizing the resulting terms as the prime factorizations of the terms in the harmonic series, and the right equality uses the standard formula for a geometric series.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It follows from these manipulations that the sum of reciprocals of primes, on the right hand of this equality, must diverge, for if it converged these steps could be reversed to show that the harmonic series also converges, which it does not.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] An immediate corollary is that there are infinitely many prime numbers, because a finite sum cannot diverge.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Although Euler's work is not considered adequately rigorous by the standards of modern mathematics, it can be made rigorous by taking more care with limits and error bounds.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Euler's conclusion that the partial sums of reciprocals of primes grow as a double logarithm of the number of terms has been confirmed by later mathematicians as one of Mertens' theorems, and can be seen as a precursor to the prime number theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Bounding the final error term more precisely remains an open problem, known as Dirichlet's divisor problem.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] More serious applications of this problem include sampling all variations of a manufactured product for its quality control, and the connectivity of random graphs.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In situations of this form, once there are k items remaining to be collected out of a total of n equally-likely items, the probability of collecting a new item in a single random choice is $k/n$ and the expected number of random choices needed until a new item is collected is $n/k$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Summing over all values of k from n down to 1 shows that the total expected number of random choices needed to collect all items is $nH_{n}$ , where $H_{n}$ is the n th harmonic number.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The quicksort algorithm for sorting a set of items can be analyzed using the harmonic numbers.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The algorithm operates by choosing one item as a "pivot", comparing it to all the others, and recursively sorting the two subsets of items whose comparison places them before the pivot and after the pivot.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In either its average-case complexity (with the assumption that all input permutations are equally likely) or in its expected time analysis of worst-case inputs with a random choice of pivot, all of the items are equally likely to be chosen as the pivot.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] For such cases, one can compute the probability that two items are ever compared with each other, throughout the recursion, as a function of the number of other items that separate them in the final sorted order.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] If items x and y are separated by k other items, then the algorithm will make a comparison between x and y only when, as the recursion progresses, it picks x or y as a pivot before picking any of the other k items between them.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Because each of these $k+2$ items is equally likely to be chosen first, this happens with probability ${\tfrac {2}{k+2}}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It is conditionally convergent by the alternating series test, but not absolutely convergent.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It can be extended by analytic continuation to a holomorphic function on all complex numbers except $x=1$ , where the extended function has a simple pole.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The random harmonic series is $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {s_{n}}{n}},$ where the values $s_{n}$ are independent and identically distributed random variables that take the two values $+1$ and $-1$ with equal probability ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It converges with probability 1, as can be seen by using the Kolmogorov three-series theorem or of the closely related Kolmogorov maximal inequality.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] This function is close to ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ for values between $-1$ and 1 , with the $g(0)\approx 0.2499943958$ to ten decimal places.
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] It decreases asymptotically like a normal distribution for values greater than 3 or less than $-3$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] Intermediate between these ranges, at the values $\pm 2$ , the probability density is ${\tfrac {1}{8}}-\varepsilon$ for a nonzero but very small value $\varepsilon <10^{-42}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] The depleted harmonic series where all of the terms in which the digit 9 appears anywhere in the denominator are removed can be shown to converge to the value 22.92067661926415034816....
[src:mellin-transform/harmonic-sum] In fact, when all the terms containing any particular string of digits (in any base) are removed, the series converges.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] In mathematics, the **Mellin inversion formula** (named after Hjalmar Mellin) tells us conditions under which the inverse Mellin transform, or equivalently the inverse two-sided Laplace transform, are defined and recover the transformed function.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] is absolutely convergent when ⁠ $a<\Re (s)<b$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] Then f is recoverable via the inverse Mellin transform from its Mellin transform ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] These results can be obtained by relating the Mellin transform to the Fourier transform by a change of variables and then applying an appropriate version of the Fourier inversion theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] The boundedness condition on $\varphi (s)$ can be strengthened if $f(x)$ is continuous.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] On the other hand, if we are willing to accept an original f which is a generalized function, we may relax the boundedness condition on $\varphi$ to simply make it of polynomial growth in any closed strip contained in the open strip ⁠ $a<\Re (s)<b$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] We may also define a Banach space version of this theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] Here functions, identical everywhere except on a set of measure zero, are identified.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-inversion-theorem] these theorems can be immediately applied to it also.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] In mathematics, the **Mellin transform** is an integral transform that may be regarded as the multiplicative version of the two-sided Laplace transform.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] Conditions under which this inversion is valid are given in the Mellin inversion theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The transform was introduced in 1859 by Bernhard Riemann.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The Mellin transform also connects the Newton series or binomial transform together with the Poisson generating function, by means of the Poisson–Mellin–Newton cycle.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The Mellin transform may also be viewed as the Gelfand transform for the convolution algebra of the locally compact abelian group of positive real numbers with multiplication.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The Mellin transform of the function $f(x)=e^{-x}$ is $\Gamma (s)=\int _{0}^{\infty }x^{s-1}e^{-x}dx$ where $\Gamma (s)$ is the gamma function. $\Gamma (s)$ is a meromorphic function with simple poles at ⁠ $z=0,-1,-2,\dots$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] This integral is known as the Cahen–Mellin integral.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] Since ${\textstyle \int _{0}^{\infty }x^{a}dx}$ is not convergent for any value of ⁠ $a\in \mathbb {R}$ ⁠, the Mellin transform is not defined for polynomial functions defined on the whole positive real axis.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] However, by defining it to be zero on different sections of the real axis, it is possible to take the Mellin transform.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] Thus ${\mathcal {M}}f(s)$ has a simple pole at $s=-a$ and is thus defined for ⁠ $\Re (s)>-a$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] It is possible to use the Mellin transform to produce one of the fundamental formulas for the Riemann zeta function, ⁠ $\zeta (s)$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] For ⁠ $\alpha ,\beta \in \mathbb {R}$ ⁠, let the open strip $\langle \alpha ,\beta \rangle$ be defined to be all $s\in \mathbb {C}$ such that $s=\sigma +it$ with ⁠ $\alpha <\sigma <\beta$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The **fundamental strip** of ${\mathcal {M}}f(s)$ is defined to be the largest open strip on which it is defined.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] As seen by this example, the asymptotics of the function as $x\to 0^{+}$ define the left endpoint of its fundamental strip, and the asymptotics of the function as $x\to +\infty$ define its right endpoint.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] To summarize using Big O notation, if f is $O(x^{a})$ as $x\to 0^{+}$ and $O(x^{b})$ as ⁠ $x\to +\infty$ ⁠, then ${\mathcal {M}}f(s)$ is defined in the strip ⁠ $\langle -a,-b\rangle$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] An application of this can be seen in the gamma function, ⁠ $\Gamma (s)$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The properties in this table may be found in Bracewell (2000) and Erdélyi (1954).
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] This gives following theorem: Let $f(x)$ be a function with well-defined Mellin transform ${\tilde {f}}(s)={\mathcal {M}}\{f\}(s)$ in the fundamental strip ⁠ $\alpha <\Re s<\beta$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] In the study of Hilbert spaces, the Mellin transform is often posed in a slightly different way.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] In probability theory, the Mellin transform is an essential tool in studying the distributions of products of random variables.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] This transform exists for all ⁠ s ⁠ in some complex strip ⁠ $D=\{s:a\leq \Re (s)\leq b\}$ ⁠, where ⁠ $a\leq 0\leq b$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The Mellin transform ${\mathcal {M}}_{X}(it)$ of a random variable ⁠ X ⁠ uniquely determines its distribution function ⁠ $F_{X}$ ⁠.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The Mellin transform is widely used in computer science for the analysis of algorithms because of its scale invariance property.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The magnitude of the Mellin Transform of a scaled function is identical to the magnitude of the original function for purely imaginary inputs.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] This scale invariance property is analogous to the Fourier Transform's shift invariance property.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] The magnitude of a Fourier transform of a time-shifted function is identical to the magnitude of the Fourier transform of the original function.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] This property is useful in image recognition.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] An image of an object is easily scaled when the object is moved towards or away from the camera.
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] In quantum mechanics and especially quantum field theory, Fourier space is enormously useful and used extensively because momentum and position are Fourier transforms of each other (for instance, Feynman diagrams are much more easily computed in momentum space).
[src:mellin-transform/mellin-transform] Liam Fitzpatrick, Jared Kaplan, João Penedones, Suvrat Raju, and Balt C. van Rees showed that Mellin space serves an analogous role in the context of the AdS/CFT correspondence.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] In mathematics, in the area of complex analysis, **Nachbin's theorem** (named after Leopoldo Nachbin) is a result used to establish bounds on the growth rates for analytic functions.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] In particular, Nachbin's theorem may be used to give the domain of convergence of the **generalized Borel transform**, also called **Nachbin summation**.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] This article provides a brief review of growth rates, including the idea of a **function of exponential type**.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Classification of growth rates based on type help provide a finer tool than big O or Landau notation, since a number of theorems about the analytic structure of the bounded function and its integral transforms can be stated.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Here, the complex variable z was written as $z=re^{i\theta }$ to emphasize that the limit must hold in all directions $\theta$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Letting $\alpha$ stand for the infimum of all such $\alpha$ , one then says that the function f is of *exponential type $\alpha$*.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Then one says that $\sin(\pi z)$ is of exponential type $\pi$ , since $\pi$ is the smallest number that bounds the growth of $\sin(\pi z)$ along the imaginary axis.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] So, for this example, Carlson's theorem cannot apply, as it requires functions of exponential type less than $\pi$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Additional function types may be defined for other bounding functions besides the exponential function.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Comparison functions are necessarily entire, which follows from the ratio test.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] If $\tau$ is the infimum of all such $\tau$ one says that f is of $\Psi$ -type $\tau$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] This is naturally connected to the root test and can be considered a relative of the Cauchy–Hadamard theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Nachbin's theorem has immediate applications in Cauchy theorem-like situations, and for integral transforms.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] where the contour of integration γ encircles the disk $|w|\leq \tau$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] This generalizes the usual **Borel transform** for functions of exponential type, where $\Psi (t)=e^{t}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] The integral form for the generalized Borel transform follows as well.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] The ordinary Borel transform is regained by setting $\alpha (t)=-e^{-t}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] Note that the integral form of the Borel transform is the Laplace transform.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] where ${\textstyle g(s)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}s^{-n}}$ , $f(t)$ may or may not be of exponential type, and the kernel $K(u)$ has a Mellin transform.
[src:mellin-transform/nachbin-s-theorem] The solution can be obtained using Nachbin summation as $f(x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {a_{n}}{M(n+1)}}x^{n}$ with the $a_{n}$ from $g(s)$ and with $M(n)$ the Mellin transform of $K(u)$ .
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] In mathematics, and more particularly in analytic number theory, **Perron's formula** is a formula discovered by Oskar Perron to calculate the sum of an arithmetic function, by means of an inverse Mellin transform.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] Presume the Dirichlet series to be uniformly convergent for $\Re (s)>\sigma$ .
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] Here, the prime on the summation indicates that the last term of the sum must be multiplied by 1/2 when *x* is an integer.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] The integral is not a convergent Lebesgue integral; it is understood as the Cauchy principal value.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] The formula requires that *c* > 0, *c* > σ, and *x* > 0.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] This is nothing but a Laplace transform under the variable change $x=e^{t}.$ Inverting it one gets Perron's formula.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] Proofs of Perron's formula have been published by Tom M.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] Because of its general relationship to Dirichlet series, the formula is commonly applied to many number-theoretic sums.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] and $\chi (n)$ is a Dirichlet character.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] Other examples appear in the articles on the Mertens function and the von Mangoldt function.
[src:mellin-transform/perron-s-formula] The Perron formula is the special case of the test function $f(1/x)=\theta (x-1),$ for $\theta (x)$ the Heaviside step function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] In mathematics, **Ramanujan's master theorem**, named after Srinivasa Ramanujan, is a technique that provides an analytic expression for the Mellin transform of an analytic function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] where ${\textstyle \Gamma (s)}$ is the gamma function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] It was widely used by Ramanujan to calculate definite integrals and infinite series.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Higher-dimensional versions of this theorem also appear in quantum physics through Feynman diagrams.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] A similar result was also obtained by Glaisher.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] which gets converted to the above form after substituting ${\textstyle \lambda (n)\equiv {\frac {\varphi (n)}{\,\Gamma (1+n)\,}}}$ and using the functional equation for the gamma function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The integral above is convergent for ${\textstyle 0<\operatorname {\mathcal {Re}} (s)<1}$ subject to growth conditions on ${\textstyle \varphi }$ .
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] A proof subject to "natural" assumptions (though not the weakest necessary conditions) to Ramanujan's master theorem was provided by G.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Hardy(chapter XI) employing the residue theorem and the well-known Mellin inversion theorem.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] which is valid for ${\textstyle 0<\operatorname {\mathcal {Re}} (s)<1}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] where ${\textstyle \zeta (k)}$ is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The solution is remarkable in that it is able to interpolate across the major identities for the gamma function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The bracket integration method (method of brackets) applies Ramanujan's master theorem to a broad range of integrals.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The bracket integration method generates the integrand's series expansion, creates a bracket series, identifies the series coefficient and formula parameters and computes the integral.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] This section identifies the integration formulas for integrand's with and without consecutive integer exponents and for single and double integrals.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The integration formula for double integrals may be generalized to any multiple integral.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] In all cases, there is a parameter value ${\textstyle n^{\ast }}$ or array of parameter values ${\textstyle N^{\ast }}$ that solves one or more linear equations derived from the exponent terms of the integrand's series expansion.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] This section describes the integration formula for a double integral whose integrand's series expansion may not contain consecutive integer exponents.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] In some cases, there may be more sums than variables.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] For example, if the integrand is a product of 3 functions of a common single variable, and each function is converted to a series expansion sum, the integrand is now a product of 3 sums, each sum corresponding to a distinct series expansion.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] The free summation indices ${\textstyle {\bar {n}}_{1},\ldots ,{\bar {n}}_{f}}$ are elements of set ${\textstyle F}$ .
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Matrices ${\textstyle A,C}$ and ${\textstyle N^{\ast }}$ contain matrix elements that multiply or sum with the non-summation indices.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] This algorithm describes how to apply the integral formulas.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Transform the integrand's power series to a bracket series.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Obtain the complexity index, formula parameters and series coefficient function.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Identify parameter ${\textstyle a}$ or (zero complexity index, single integral) or compute ${\textstyle \det |A|}$ (all other cases) from the associated linear equations.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Identify the series coefficient function ${\textstyle \varphi ()}$ of the bracket series.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] If the complexity index is negative, return integral cannot be assigned a value.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] If the complexity index is zero, select the formula from table 2 for zero complexity index, single or multiple integral, compute the integral value with this formula, and return this integral value.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] If the complexity index is positive, select the formula from table 2 for positive complexity index, and compute the integral value as a series expansion with this formula for all possible choices of the free summation indices.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Select the lowest complexity index, convergent series expansion, adding series that converge in the same region.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] If the series expansion is non-null and non-divergent, return this series expansion as the integral value.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Express the integrand as a power series.
[src:mellin-transform/ramanujan-s-master-theorem] Complexity index is 1 as 3 sums and 2 brackets.
